Implement the private `do_delete/2` function. It takes a trie node and a list of
graphemes (the remaining characters of the word being removed) and returns a new
node with that word unmarked, pruning any nodes that become useless.

When the character list is empty, you have reached the node that terminates the
word: clear its `terminal` flag (set it to `false`) and return the node. Do not
touch its children — other longer words may still pass through here (deleting
"car" must not affect "card").

When the character list is `[char | rest]`, fetch the child node stored under
`char` (it is guaranteed to exist, since `delete/2` only calls `do_delete/2` for
words already present), and recursively delete `rest` from it to get an updated
child. Then decide whether to keep or drop that child: if the updated child is no
longer terminal AND has no children of its own, it is dead weight — remove `char`
from the current node's `children`. Otherwise, store the updated child back under
`char`. Return the current node with its `children` updated accordingly.

